%T A397220 597,611,671,679,711,713,717,731,737,831,837,897,973,979,1131,1137,
%U A397220 1311,1313,1317,1379,1797,1971,3113,3131,3173,3179,4197,4311,4313,4317,4797,6137,6179,7197,7971,31373
%N A397220 Composite numbers with at least three digits such that every proper contiguous substring of length at least 2 is prime.
%C A397220 A term is a composite integer with at least three digits all of whose proper contiguous substrings (in base 10) of length at least 2 are prime.
%C A397220 The sequence is finite. Suppose there existed an element with six or more digits. Then its first five digits would form a proper contiguous substring and hence must be prime. Moreover, every contiguous substring of length at least 2 within that five-digit prefix would also be prime. Thus the prefix would be a term of A131648. But A131648 contains no five-digit terms. Therefore this sequence contains no terms with six or more digits. The sequence contains exactly 53 terms.
%C A397220 The unique five-digit term is 31373 = 137 * 229.
%C A397220 This sequence is the composite analog of A131648. Whereas A131648 consists of primes whose every contiguous substring of length at least 2 is prime, the present sequence consists of composites whose proper contiguous substrings of length at least 2 are all prime.
%e A397220 1311 is a term because its proper contiguous substrings of length at least 2 are 13, 31, 11, 131, 311, all prime, while 1311 itself is composite.
%Y A397220 Cf. A131648 (prime analog), A366826, A211683, A035244.
%K A397220 nonn,base,fini,full,new
%O A397220 1,1
